<font color="#FF0000">THE SITE IS DOING FINE</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 17  6:01:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Class Lass has been defended by a couple of posters - myself included. A risk is taken when someone posts sans email address. I am sure that she understands. She has contacted me and John Ratliff b/c.<br><br>
There has been a problem of sorts for a long time on this site where people have posted anonymously in one form or another. When the site first took off a year ago, I spotted these!<br><br>
I have absolutely no problem with the people who have supposedly &quot;taken over the site&quot;. It has been said over and over again how &quot;acceptance aids in the healing process&quot;. In some circles Vietnam Veterans will never gain acceptance. I understand this. I make it a point to avoid these places. For some odd reason those who fail to gain acceptance here are slow to understand. Not everyone is going to like everyone else. That is the way of the world. The result should be that we renew our search and find where we do belong. But no, the dullwitted delude themselves by staying.<br><br>
I have had the privilege to engage in dialogue with most of the veterans who remain on this site. At times I have stood on the opposite side of the dialogue. As far as my point of view goes, I still am on the opposite end of the spectrum. It has been proven by the evolution of the dialogue that our differences don't mean a damn thing. We are vets and there is much more that we agree on that binds us closely.<br><br>
People like the anonymous poster(S) don't want anyone to find common ground or acceptance. They want ongoing discord. It is very obvious to me. <br><br>
In their anonymity they question the ability of others to take a stand! <br><br>
If there are any out there, vet or non vet, feel free to post whatever you like. The going may get rough. Whoever said that earning respect was an easy matter?
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


